<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-452-762  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 452 762.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Desktop Publishing  May 7 1990 v4 n9 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>3Com's 3+ Open: OS/2 LAN Manager at the starting gate. (editorial)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   Open Software Architecture (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>3Com's 3+OPEN: OS/2 LAN Manager At the Starting Gate ONE OF THE MOSTsignificant features of OS/2 is that it was designed from the first tosupport distributed, networked computing.andP;  And although OS/2 has provedslower at fulfilling its promise than many developers and users would like,we believe that it will grow into a solid foundation for the publishingapplications of the nineties.andP;  Indeed, if the evidence of the past is anyguide, publishing will be one of the driving markets for this operatingsystem.andP;  Publishing is inherently a group activity for which no standalonecomputing system will be satisfactory in the long run.andP;  For this reason, weare intensely interested in the maturation process that OS/2 and its networkcomponent, LAN Manager, are going through.andM;In this issue, we take a look at the current version of LAN Manager asembodied in one particular product: 3Com's 3+Open, which we have been usingin the daily operation of our Malibu office for the past few months.andO;Although much of our testing was done with pre-release software, we havegotten a feel for several critical issues such as ease of installation andadministration, system performance and overall usability.andP;  We conclude that,although 3+Open has a lot going for it, there are enough problems that wearen't quite ready to make the migration from the earlier 3+ software.andM;A subtext in our story is the ongoing competition between the LAN Managercamp and the advocates of Novell's NetWare 386.andP;  Although this isn't really astory about Novell, it is impossible to discuss PC networks without talkingabout the current market leader.andP;  Novell and Microsoft (and its OEMs like3Com) are both determined that their own products will dominate the desktopnetworking picture.andO;</TEXT></DOC>